29
00:09:01,458 --> 00:09:05,754
I'm sure they'd love to meet you.

30
00:09:06,963 --> 00:09:13,053
- Who are you?
- My name is Todd Bowden.

31
00:09:13,220 --> 00:09:18,183
I really want to talk to you.
Could you let me in for a minute?

32
00:09:18,391 --> 00:09:22,312
Please, Mr. Dussander.

33
00:09:26,108 --> 00:09:30,278
All of this because you saw
an old man in a raincoat?

34
00:09:30,445 --> 00:09:34,616
It wasn't that easy.
These pictures are 40 years old.

35
00:09:34,825 --> 00:09:37,786
But they looked like those I took.

36
00:09:37,994 --> 00:09:44,334
- You took photographs of me?
- Yeah, but even then I wasn't sure.

37
00:09:44,501 --> 00:09:48,964
I needed real proof. So I dusted
your mail box for fingerprints.

38
00:09:49,881 --> 00:09:55,971
That's harder than people think.
You need a lot of stuff.

39
00:09:56,179 --> 00:10:01,768
- You were at the movies.
- You dusted my mail box.

40
00:10:01,935 --> 00:10:05,772
You took photographs of me.
What else did you do?

41
00:10:05,981 --> 00:10:10,485
I had a copy of your fingerprints
from your lsraeli wanted sheet.

42
00:10:10,652 --> 00:10:14,072
It's all on database
at the university.

43
00:10:16,741 --> 00:10:20,328
Are you okay?

44
00:10:21,538 --> 00:10:27,002
- Would you care for a drink?
- How about milk?

45
00:10:36,344 --> 00:10:42,517
- Have you told your parents?
- Do you think I'm crazy?

46
00:10:43,393 --> 00:10:48,690
It takes eight "compares"
to get a print accepted in court.

47
00:10:48,857 --> 00:10:53,361
One or two is not hard to find,
but eight, that's really tough.

48
00:10:53,528 --> 00:11:00,827
It all sounds very exciting, but
all your work has been for nothing.

49
00:11:00,994 --> 00:11:04,372
I found 14 compares.

50
00:11:07,751 --> 00:11:14,633
Boy, what you have done ...
I have to explain this to you.

51
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:19,930
- What you have done is a violation.
- Like decompression experiments?

52
00:11:20,097 --> 00:11:25,519
- That's a violation.
- I'm calling the police.

53
00:11:25,685 --> 00:11:29,439
Your father's going
to beat your behind.

54
00:11:29,606 --> 00:11:34,736
- He doesn't believe in violence.
- They should start.

55
00:11:44,204 --> 00:11:47,874
My name is Denker.

56
00:11:50,335 --> 00:11:53,547
Arthur Denker.

57
00:11:55,006 --> 00:12:01,096
I'm an American.
I became a citizen in 1955.

58
00:12:04,891 --> 00:12:08,228
I vote.

59
00:12:09,521 --> 00:12:16,111
You've no right to come here
and say these lies about me.

60
00:12:17,654 --> 00:12:23,326
I have your fingerprints.
I have your photographs.

61
00:12:23,493 --> 00:12:28,623
One way or another,
I'll get them to the right people.

62
00:12:33,587 --> 00:12:37,799
This is unbelievable.

63
00:12:41,428 --> 00:12:44,848
What do you want? Tell me.

64
00:12:47,017 --> 00:12:50,687
- I want to hear about it.
- Hear about what?

65
00:12:50,854 --> 00:12:54,775
The stories. Everything.

66
00:12:55,817 --> 00:12:58,570
What everything?

67
00:12:58,737 --> 00:13:03,033
Everything they're afraid
to show us in school.

68
00:13:03,200 --> 00:13:06,953
You were there.
You did those things.

69
00:13:07,204 --> 00:13:12,334
No one can tell it better than you.
That's all I want.

70
00:13:12,542 --> 00:13:18,006
Then I'll leave you alone.
And just so you know ...

71
00:13:20,383 --> 00:13:23,136
Everything that I have on you, -

72
00:13:23,303 --> 00:13:27,432
- the compares, the wanted sheet,
all the photographs, -

73
00:13:27,599 --> 00:13:33,063
- are in a safe place. If anything
happens to me, they'll be found.

74
00:13:36,441 --> 00:13:41,238
Why should I consider doing this?

75
00:13:41,947 --> 00:13:46,410
Because you hung up the phone.

76
00:14:07,848 --> 00:14:11,268
Judging by the results
of your first exam, -

77
00:14:11,435 --> 00:14:15,981
- for most of you, we moved
too fast through chapter one.

78
00:14:17,149 --> 00:14:23,238
How many of you
think you know what sociology is?

79
00:14:26,825 --> 00:14:32,622
As I thought.
All right, turn to chapter two.

80
00:14:39,963 --> 00:14:44,217
Once they were in the chamber,
how long did it take? A minute?

81
00:14:45,260 --> 00:14:50,056
No, the Prussic acid
took about 15 minutes.

82
00:14:50,265 --> 00:14:55,979
But the monoxide could take
an hour, sometimes more.

83
00:14:56,730 --> 00:15:01,610
What happened to them ... exactly?

84
00:15:04,446 --> 00:15:09,493
It was a mess. They would
lose control of their bodies.

85
00:15:09,701 --> 00:15:15,040
They vomited, urinated
and defecated themselves.

86
00:15:15,207 --> 00:15:19,628
Even though the gas
came through vents in the ceiling, -

87
00:15:19,836 --> 00:15:22,464
- they climbed up on each other, -

88
00:15:22,672 --> 00:15:27,636
- desperately reaching for fresh air
that wasn't there.

89
00:15:27,803 --> 00:15:34,810
- There was a mountain of bodies.
- What about the children?

90
00:15:36,603 --> 00:15:40,440
On the bottom.

91
00:15:41,691 --> 00:15:47,489
Did anyone ever survive it?

92
00:15:49,533 --> 00:15:56,832
One time, the gas didn't work.

93
00:15:56,998 --> 00:16:03,338
There was a leak in the pipes,
so oxygen mixed with the monoxide.

94
00:16:04,256 --> 00:16:10,178
It was horrible. After an hour,
they were still moving.

95
00:16:10,720 --> 00:16:16,810
Stumbling around the room
like drunks, their eyes glassy.

96
00:16:17,602 --> 00:16:20,313
What did you do?

97
00:16:20,480 --> 00:16:24,651
I ordered more gas,
but we didn't know about the leak.

98
00:16:24,818 --> 00:16:30,449
Soon they began to twitch all over,
like they were dancing.

99
00:16:30,615 --> 00:16:37,539
Some fell to their knees,
laughing in a high-pitched scream.

100
00:16:38,457 --> 00:16:42,586
Even the guards were frightened.

101
00:16:44,921 --> 00:16:51,803
They didn't die. After two hours,
I sent five men in with rifles.

102
00:16:57,225 --> 00:17:01,438
It's getting dark.
Your mother will be worried.

103
00:17:01,605 --> 00:17:06,735
Shit! I've got to go. Tomorrow,
I want to hear the end of this.

104
00:17:06,902 --> 00:17:10,155
The end?

105
00:17:12,908 --> 00:17:16,411
The end.

106
00:18:12,592 --> 00:18:17,347
Todd, are you up?
Let's go. Joey's outside.

107
00:18:17,514 --> 00:18:23,937
- Tell him I'm coming.
- I woke you half an hour ago.

108
00:18:24,813 --> 00:18:29,067
- Todd?
- I must have fallen asleep.

109
00:18:29,234 --> 00:18:34,781
I'm going to see a client tonight.
There's some chicken in the fridge.

110
00:18:34,948 --> 00:18:41,538
- I'm eating at Mr. Denker's house.
- And do what, watch TV?

111
00:18:41,705 --> 00:18:46,752
I read books to him.
Don't worry about it.

112
00:18:46,960 --> 00:18:54,176
Invite him over here.
Daddy and I still want to meet him.

113
00:18:54,342 --> 00:18:56,636
The policeman said:

114
00:18:56,845 --> 00:19:01,975
"Mr. Denker, if you can't see
the road, you shouldn't be driving.

115
00:19:02,184 --> 00:19:05,020
"How many fingers am I holding up?

116
00:19:05,187 --> 00:19:09,649
I said,
"Well now, officer, let me guess."

117
00:19:10,442 --> 00:19:13,612
"One?"

118
00:19:15,489 --> 00:19:20,452
That was the end of my driving
in America. I take the bus.

119
00:19:21,161 --> 00:19:27,918
I'm now in a wheelchair, but
my sight is not what it used to be.

120
00:19:30,253 --> 00:19:34,091
That's a white-tailed buck.

121
00:19:34,299 --> 00:19:40,555
- We used to live in Carolina.
- Dick shot that seven years ago.

122
00:19:40,722 --> 00:19:45,393
Your grandson never told me
he came from a family of hunters.

123
00:19:45,602 --> 00:19:50,357
- Todd never took a shine to guns.
- No, he's good at other things.

124
00:19:50,524 --> 00:19:55,570
- Baseball is Todd's game.
- Arthur, you want a cigar?

125
00:19:55,779 --> 00:20:00,659
I'll have one of my cigarettes.
Where are they?

126
00:20:00,826 --> 00:20:04,496
Let me help you with that.

127
00:20:04,663 --> 00:20:11,753
Your generosity humbles me.
Thank you for an enchanting evening.

128
00:20:16,133 --> 00:20:21,805
Arthur, can I ask you
a personal question?

129
00:20:22,681 --> 00:20:26,435
What did you do during the war?

130
00:20:30,313 --> 00:20:34,317
I was in the reserves,
as were most young men, Victor.

131
00:20:34,484 --> 00:20:38,697
My poor eyesight
kept me out of combat, thank God.

132
00:20:38,864 --> 00:20:45,996
I spent most of the war
washing hospital linen.

133
00:20:50,500 --> 00:20:53,253
You're quiet tonight.

134
00:20:53,420 --> 00:20:57,340
I'm sorry, it's just that
I've heard all these stories before.

135
00:20:57,549 --> 00:21:03,138
- Todd!
- The boy's just being honest.

136
00:21:04,681 --> 00:21:09,478
That's a privilege that men
must sometimes give up.

137
00:21:12,063 --> 00:21:15,484
That reminds me ...

138
00:21:15,650 --> 00:21:23,075
It must have been my first year
at the university ...

139
00:21:23,241 --> 00:21:28,455
My men took turns shooting them,
but there were so many.

140
00:21:28,622 --> 00:21:35,670
Three bodies were packed into each
oven. They were ground into ash.

141
00:21:35,837 --> 00:21:41,176
A whole town was
wiped off the face of the earth.

142
00:21:53,730 --> 00:21:58,693
Still it wasn't enough for Himmler.
It was a dark year.

143
00:21:58,860 --> 00:22:03,657
He ordered every Jew in Kiev
to come to the Babi Jar ravine.

144
00:22:03,907 --> 00:22:08,870
Remember, the 20's
were a desperate time in Germany.

145
00:22:09,037 --> 00:22:13,542
The Treaty of Versailles
had left us crippled.

146
00:22:13,750 --> 00:22:17,587
They would hide.

147
00:22:17,754 --> 00:22:22,884
We always found them. If the dogs
didn't, smoke and fire would.

148
00:22:23,093 --> 00:22:27,389
We would round them up
and march them out to a large pit.

149
00:22:27,556 --> 00:22:31,393
At the time, the shooting
was no longer killing.

150
00:22:31,601 --> 00:22:34,896
Killing was no longer death.

151
00:22:35,105 --> 00:22:39,568
I will never forget
the sound that night.

152
00:22:39,734 --> 00:22:43,739
So many of them
on top of each another like that.

153
00:22:43,905 --> 00:22:49,035
After a few hours,
they began to settle.

154
00:22:52,080 --> 00:22:56,001
A head would fall.

155
00:22:56,209 --> 00:22:59,463
An arm would drop.

156
00:23:03,008 --> 00:23:07,888
It was a bit like the sound
of blowing leaves.

157
00:23:10,223 --> 00:23:13,101
What did it feel like?

158
00:23:26,531 --> 00:23:29,326
It had to be done.

159
00:23:29,493 --> 00:23:35,665
A door had been opened and
couldn't be shut. It was the end ...

160
00:23:35,832 --> 00:23:38,960
You don't understand.

161
00:23:40,545 --> 00:23:43,507
You've done it a million times.
Let's go!

162
00:24:04,444 --> 00:24:07,364
All right, that's it. Take a shower.

163
00:24:08,865 --> 00:24:12,285
- Where have you been?
- What do you mean?

164
00:24:12,536 --> 00:24:17,749
I tried to phone you.
There's a party on Saturday night.

165
00:24:17,958 --> 00:24:22,504
- I've been busy.
- Too busy for your best friend?

166
00:24:22,712 --> 00:24:28,969
- I've been studying a lot.
- Are you going to go?

167
00:24:29,177 --> 00:24:35,434
- I don't know if I can get the car.
- I know someone who'll drive you.

168
00:26:26,670 --> 00:26:30,173
I've been accepted!

169
00:26:30,382 --> 00:26:34,302
The Ritzy Vista Country Club.
My life 's ambition.

170
00:26:34,511 --> 00:26:41,101
Officer, can you tell me which bus
goes to the Ritzy Vista Club?

171
00:26:41,351 --> 00:26:44,229
Here it is.

172
00:26:44,396 --> 00:26:50,736
- Do you go by the country club?
- Very humorous.

173
00:27:13,383 --> 00:27:17,429
- Wake up.
- I'll kill you!

174
00:27:21,683 --> 00:27:24,603
I thought you were dead.

175
00:27:24,770 --> 00:27:30,942
It's Saturday. Since when do you
come here on Saturdays?

176
00:27:31,151 --> 00:27:35,572
I brought you something.
Aren't you going to open it?

177
00:27:36,406 --> 00:27:40,577
Wait.
Let me pull the shades down.

178
00:27:42,287 --> 00:27:45,582
- What for?
- To be safe.

179
00:27:45,749 --> 00:27:51,922
- The hell with this. You open it.
- Relax. Open it.

180
00:28:02,265 --> 00:28:06,436
You wrapped it yourself, I see.

181
00:28:21,743 --> 00:28:25,914
- Merry Christmas.
- Mary mother of God!

182
00:28:27,457 --> 00:28:32,504
- Where did you get this?
- It's pretty real.

183
00:28:37,551 --> 00:28:45,183
"E.F. Montgomery Costumes,
Tappan Zee, New Jersey."

184
00:28:46,435 --> 00:28:51,231
- Try it on.
- Have you lost your mind?

185
00:28:51,481 --> 00:28:55,944
- Why would I put that on?
- I thought you would like it.

186
00:28:57,404 --> 00:29:01,158
Like it?
You're a bigger fool than I thought.

187
00:29:01,366 --> 00:29:05,996
Maybe I'll put it on
and do a little shopping, right?

188
00:29:06,163 --> 00:29:09,499
For this indignity,
I should smash you.

189
00:29:09,666 --> 00:29:14,880
This is nothing compared to what
the lsraelis would do to you.

190
00:29:15,088 --> 00:29:20,385
Don't forget that and don't ever
forget the file I have on you.

191
00:29:20,552 --> 00:29:24,890
I tried to do things the nice way,
but fine, we'll do it the hard way.

192
00:29:25,056 --> 00:29:29,936
You'll put this on because
I want to see you in it. Move!

193
00:30:14,064 --> 00:30:18,527
- I see I've been promoted.
- Yeah, it's all they had.

194
00:30:18,693 --> 00:30:21,530
But it's a perfect fit.

195
00:30:21,822 --> 00:30:26,952
- It itches like hell.
- Quiet.

196
00:30:28,245 --> 00:30:32,791
- Put the hat on.
- Please!

197
00:30:32,958 --> 00:30:36,711
Please, put the hat on.

198
00:31:04,281 --> 00:31:07,701
Attention.

199
00:31:15,792 --> 00:31:19,087
What's so funny?

200
00:31:20,088 --> 00:31:24,009
March. Do it.

201
00:31:25,635 --> 00:31:29,139
I'm serious.

202
00:31:35,812 --> 00:31:39,816
Stop fucking around. March!

203
00:31:44,196 --> 00:31:47,574
That's it. March.

204
00:31:49,493 --> 00:31:53,246
Face right.

205
00:31:55,207 --> 00:31:57,584
March.

206
00:31:57,751 --> 00:32:01,129
Face right.

